AI Workflow for Developers - Team Project

Overview
This repository contains the shared project for the Emerging Technologies module.
The project demonstrates different AI workflow systems designed by the team members.
Each system uses n8n as an orchestration platform and connects external services such as Azure DevOps, GitHub, GitHub Actions and LLM providers.
This README explains how to start the local n8n environment, import the workflows and execute the different systems.

<br>

Repository Structure
docker-compose.yml
workflows/
n8n_data/
.env
README.md

<br>

Local n8n Self-Hosting Setup
The project uses a self-hosted n8n instance running locally with Docker.
The docker-compose.yml file is already included in the project.
Before starting n8n, the following local resources must be available:
Docker Desktop installed and running
Git installed
The project repository cloned locally
A local .env file if environment variables are required
A local n8n_data directory for persistent n8n data

<br>

Clone the Project Repository
Open a terminal and clone the project repository.
Replace the URL if another remote is used.
git clone <repository-url>
cd AI-Workflow-Nutrition

<br>

Prepare Local n8n Data
The n8n_data directory is used to persist the local n8n database and configuration.
If the directory does not exist, create it before starting Docker.
mkdir n8n_data
The .env file can be used for local configuration values if needed.
This file must not be committed.

<br>

Start n8n
From the root of the project, run:
docker compose up -d
n8n is then available at:
http://localhost:5678
At first launch, n8n asks to create a local user account.
This account is only used for the local n8n instance.

<br>

Stop n8n
To stop the local n8n instance:
docker compose down
To restart it later:
docker compose up -d

<br>

Persistent Data
The local n8n data is stored in the n8n_data directory.
This directory is ignored by Git.
The .env file is also ignored by Git because it can contain local configuration values or secrets.
The .gitignore currently contains:
n8n_data
.env

<br>

Import Workflows in n8n
Open n8n at:
http://localhost:5678
Create the local n8n account if it does not already exist.
Open the workflow import menu.
Import the workflow JSON files from the workflows directory.
After import, each workflow can be opened, inspected and executed from the n8n interface.

<br>

Configure Credentials in n8n
The workflows require credentials to connect to external services.
Credentials are not stored in Git.
They must be configured inside the local n8n instance after the workflows are imported.
The main credential types used by the project are:
Azure DevOps Personal Access Token
GitHub Personal Access Token or GitHub Bearer Token
Mistral or OpenAI API Key
Ollama local endpoint, if a local model is used

