<br>

System 3 - Decentralized AI Software Factory
Purpose:
This system demonstrates a semi-autonomous AI Software Factory based on real User Stories.
It transforms Azure DevOps User Stories into generated code, tests, Git branches, GitHub Actions executions and reporting artifacts.
The workflow chain processes the User Story, generates implementation files, pushes a GitHub branch, triggers CI/CD and stores a final execution report.

<br>

Azure DevOps Usage
Azure DevOps is used as the backlog and User Story source for this system.
The workflows fetch User Stories from Azure DevOps and update their tags during execution.
The Azure DevOps project must already contain the User Stories to process.
User Stories intended for the decentralized AI workflow must use the expected project tags.
Example tags:
Decentralized
SEQ_001
During execution, the workflow can add tags such as:
AI_PROCESSING
AI_COMPLETED

<br>

GitHub Usage
GitHub is used as the application repository for this system.
The workflow creates feature branches, writes generated files, commits them and pushes them to GitHub.
GitHub Actions is used to execute the CI pipeline.
Application repository:
https://github.com/ValG-cpu/Nutrition-App

<br>

Running the System
The execution starts from the master workflow:
WF00 - Master Orchestrator
WF00 fetches the next eligible User Story from Azure DevOps and calls the next workflows in sequence.
The workflow chain processes the User Story, generates implementation files, pushes a GitHub branch, triggers CI/CD and stores a final execution report.

<br>

Workflow List
Bootstrap - User Story Creation
Creates simple and sequential Azure DevOps User Stories automatically.
Initializes the backlog with small atomic User Stories.
Adds the required project tags such as Decentralized and SEQ_XXX.
This workflow is used before WF00 when the backlog must be prepared automatically.

<br>

WF00 - Master Orchestrator
Coordinates the full execution chain.
Fetches eligible Azure DevOps User Stories.
Initializes the execution payload.
Calls the next workflows.

<br>

WF01 - Requirement Analysis
Analyzes the selected User Story.
Checks clarity, completeness and feasibility.
Produces a requirement analysis artifact.

<br>

WF02 - Technical Design
Produces a technical design from the analyzed User Story.
Defines files, modules, dependencies and implementation constraints.

<br>

WF03 - TDD / Test Design
Generates the test strategy.
Defines expected pytest tests.
Keeps the test scope aligned with the User Story acceptance criteria.

<br>

WF04A - Repository Context Extractor
Clones the application repository.
Extracts the existing repository structure.
Provides repository context to the code generation workflow.

<br>

WF04 - Code Generation
Generates implementation files.
Normalizes file content for transport between workflows.
Validates generated files before they are sent to Git operations.

<br>

WF05 - Repository Executor
Creates a Git branch.
Writes generated files into the application repository.
Commits and pushes the branch to GitHub.

<br>

WF06 - CI/CD Executor
Triggers GitHub Actions on the generated branch.
Polls the workflow run status.
Routes the execution depending on pipeline success or failure.

<br>

WF07 - Reporting and Traceability
Builds the final execution report.
Stores the traceability matrix.
Marks the execution as completed.

<br>

WF08 - Human Review / Recovery
Handles blocked executions.
Stores errors and recovery information.
Used when a workflow cannot continue automatically.

<br>

Troubleshooting
If n8n does not start, check that Docker Desktop is running.
If workflows cannot access external services, verify the credentials configured in n8n.
If the GitHub pipeline does not start, verify that the GitHub token has workflow permissions.
If Azure DevOps User Stories are not found, verify the tags and the Azure DevOps query used by the workflow.
If generated code fails the pipeline, check the GitHub Actions logs and the final workflow payload.

<br>

Known Limitations
The current system processes User Stories independently.
The merge or release orchestration between multiple generated branches is not automated yet.
Manual review may be required when several branches modify the same files.
The system demonstrates an industrialized AI workflow execution chain, but it does not yet include a full automated release manager.